{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"ee3d1886-99c2-4218-9261-cccc5151c821","content":"**Exit code 8** in Microsoft.Testing.Platform means \"zero tests discovered.\" VSTest returned 0 in this case, but MTP treats it as a failure by default.\n\n**Fix:** Tell MTP to treat exit code 8 as success. You have two options:\n\n### Option 1: CLI flag (in your CI pipeline)\n\n```bash\ndotnet test -- --ignore-exit-code 8\n```\n\n### Option 2: Environment variable (in CI)\n\n```bash\nexport TESTINGPLATFORM_EXITCODE_IGNORE=8\ndotnet test\n```\n\nBoth approaches make MTP return exit code 0 when no tests are found, matching the old VSTest behavior. Your project (`EnableMSTestRunner=true`) with the `#if INCLUDE_SLOW_TESTS` conditional will no longer fail CI when that symbol isn't defined.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"8788c74c-6181-49c6-99ec-c12a79e9349d","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"Now I understand the situation. The project uses MTP (EnableMSTestRunner=true) and all tests are behind `#if INCLUDE_SLOW_TESTS`. When that symbol isn't defined, zero tests are discovered, and MTP returns exit code 8 (which means \"no tests found\"), causing CI to fail.\n\nThe fix is to tell MTP to ignore exit code 8. There are a few ways:\n\n1. **In the project file**: Add `<TestingPlatformExitCodeOnNoTests>0</TestingPlatformExitCodeOnNoTests>` — wait, let me check the correct property name.\n\n\n2. **CLI argument**: Pass `--ignore-exit-code 8` when running `dotnet test`\n3. **Environment variable**: Set `TESTINGPLATFORM_EXITCODE_IGNORE=8`\n\nThe cleanest approach is probably the CLI argument or environment variable, since it directly tells MTP to treat exit code 8 as success. Now I'll walk them through the solution and show how to implement it.","outputTokens":714,"requestId":"6825:1E8CE8:728DAC:7A0D86:6A044DBC"},"id":"b65d0782-81c0-4a28-b958-513f03a39bc4","timestamp":"2026-05-13T10:09:16.175Z","parentId":"a2758c6c-c152-4f60-b332-5d02331a0832"}
